			<h3 id="comments-title">7 Responses to <em>The Best Thunderbolt Expansion Peripherals for Editors</em></h3>


			<ol class="commentlist">
					<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-303814">
		<div id="comment-303814">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/bef7204c5c5e4c85082d1847215cdeeb?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />				<cite class="fn">Seb Lloyd</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
			
			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://jonnyelwyn.co.uk/thunderbolt/the-best-thunderbolt-expansion-peripherals-for-editors/#comment-303814">
				November 26, 2013 at 12:34 pm</a>			</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

			<div class="comment-body"><p>Good run-down.<br />
When I take my laptop to clients, I&#8217;ve found it&#8217;s essential to have the network adaptor and the firewire one.<br />
The MBP has an HDMI port already, so I&#8217;m not sure why you&#8217;re obsessing over that one, unless you need two external HMDIs?<br />
More USB ports are a good thing to have, obviously. </p>
<p>As for the RAID, I settled on an ARECA 8050 after much consideration. Pain in the arse to set up, but now it&#8217;s running I get 550-650 mb/s in RAID6. It&#8217;s a pretty good machine.</p>
</div>

